Computers & Mathematics with Applications

Volume 75, Issue 7, 1 April 2018, Pages 2445-2465

Three-dimensional lattice Boltzmann simulations of high density ratio two-phase flows in porous media

Author links open overlay panel, , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.camwa.2017.12.028Get rights and content
Under an Elsevier user license
open archive

Abstract

A three-dimensional multiphase lattice Boltzmann model is implemented to study the spontaneous phase transport in complex porous media. The model is validated against the analytical solution of Young’s and Laplace’s laws. Afterward, three-dimensional porous layers are randomly generated to investigate droplet penetration into a substrate, liquid transport in a porous channel as well as extraction of a droplet from a porous medium. Effects of several geometrical and flow parameters such as porosity, density ratio, Reynolds number, Weber number, Froude number and contact angle are considered. A parametric study of the influence of main non-dimensional parameters upon the impact of liquid drops on permeable surface is performed. Results show that while increasing Froude number causes spreading of the droplet on the surface, increasing Reynolds number, Weber number, porosity and liquid-air density ratio will enhance the penetration rate into the surface. Furthermore, increasing the contact angle decreases both the spreading and the penetration rate at the same time. In the same way, for the liquid transport in a porous channel, it is found that increasing the porosity and Reynolds number will result in increasing penetration rate in the channel. For the extraction of a droplet from a porous medium, it is shown that by increasing the gravitational force and/or porosity the droplet extracts faster from the substrate.

1. Introduction

Multiphase flow in porous media is of both industrial and fundamental interests. Typical applications can be found in oil and gas transport in rock shells, groundwater flows, composite manufactories, ink-jet printing and coating among others [[1], [2], [3]]. Although most of physical phenomena engaged in such applications are micro/meso-scale, they are classically treated as macro-scale phenomena [[4], [5]] where mass, momentum and species balances are solved along with a constitutive equation such as Darcy’s law and its extension for multiphase flows [[6], [7]]. This methodology, however, has difficulties in considering the complex porous media morphologies with different heterogeneities and requires some inputs for semi-empirical equations, e.g. permeability or wetting. In addition to the above-mentioned problem, in conventional Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) techniques, in order to accurately capture the dynamic phase interfaces (i.e. fluid–fluid and/or fluid-solid), a proper use of an interface tracking method such as Level Set (LS) and/or Volume of Fluid (VoF) is indisputable [[8], [9]] which bring further complications at pore-scale. Even the macroscopic meshless methods that inherently can capture the dynamic interfaces [[10], [11], [12]] may not always realize the effects that are associated with the micro-scale structure [[13], [14]]. Therefore, the use of micro/meso-scale numerical tools became inevitable part of pore-scale modelling in the last two decades [15].

Lattice-Boltzmann Method (LBM) is one of the promising and efficient numerical tools for the simulation of fluid mechanics problems at pore-scale level. LBM consists of finite number of fictitious particles, represents an ensemble of molecules, with a given distribution on a discrete lattice mesh. The fluid system evolution is governed by microscopic interactions between these particles based on mesoscopic kinetic equations which results in particle weight redistributions on the same lattice. The macroscopic variables are then calculated through the moment integration of these distribution functions. Due to its particular nature and its local dynamics, LBM shows some advantages such as facility in implementation and parallelization, handling complex geometry, incorporating microscopic interactions, and inherently tracking the dynamic interface contact line, over conventional CFD techniques. Therefore, LBM attracts many attentions for simulations of the pore-scale phenomena in the last decade [15].

For multiphase flow in porous channels many works have been conducted in the last two decades. Among others one can mention the followings; Shan and Chen (SC) [16] proposed a multi-phase and multi-component LBM to simulate fluid flow in simple, e.g. micro-channel, and complex geometry, such as a porous medium. Their model was adopted for a gas–liquid phase change where each component was treated to be immiscible with the others. Angelopoulos et al. [17] proposed a Swift free-energy-based single component multiphase (SCMP) LBM model to simulate vapour-fluid flow in porous media. They studied the critical flooding phenomena under strong wettability conditions in a pore structure, such as formation of thin films and snap-off in narrow throats. Pan et al. [18] simulated dynamic distributions of the non-wetting phase during primary drainage by using multi component multiphase (MCMP) SC model. To relieve the numerical stability and accuracy issues of Pen et al.’s simulation, Li et al. [19] extend the multiple-relaxation-time Lattice Boltzmann model of MCMP SC.

Hao et al. [20] conducted free-energy LBM simulation of a gas diffusion layer (GDL) in a packed-sphere bed. They studied the effects of phase wettability, relative permeability of a porous material and its anisotropy on the non-wetting phase saturation. Mukherjee et al. [21] simulated the two-phase flows phenomena in the porous media of a proton exchange membrane fuel cells (PEMFC). They rigorously studied the influence of structure—wettability on the underlying two-phase behaviour and flooding dynamics in porous channels. In their work, the mobile fluid phase relative permeability is solved by using Brinkman equation. Han et al. [22] simulate the liquid water transport dynamics in the porous layer of a PEMFC. Their studies focus on the effects of the porous layer porosity and boundary liquid saturation on two-phase transport behaviours. It is noted that most of the above-mentioned studies are two-dimensional and limited to low density ratios and/or limited range of porosities.

On the other hand, results on droplet penetration/extraction into/from porous regions are scarcer. Taghilou and Rahimian [23] used the multiphase model of Lee [24] to simulate the penetration of droplet into a randomly generated porous medium. This work was recently extended by Latifiyan et al. [25] for the droplet evaporation during penetration in the porous media. It is noted that both of the above-mentioned works are two-dimensional and do not involve the wide range of medium porosity and fluid density ratios. More recently, Ge et al. [26] studied the two-dimensional droplet spreading and permeating on the porous substrates with hybrid-wettability. However, the work by Frank et al. [27] is of few three-dimensional investigations that studied the spreading of a liquid droplet on different porous surfaces. Still the porous surface in the latter work was a simple pore-space made of parallel holes of infinite length. Once more the densities of the fluid and the vapour phases in both works are of the same order of magnitude and the surface porosity is either two-dimensional or is an extension of it.

Interested readers are invited to read the three recent literature reviews on LBM for more information about its methodology and its diverse application in pore-scale [[15], [28], [29]].

As it can be seen from most of these works, the available literatures in simulation of multiphase flow and droplet penetration in porous media by LBM are limited to two-dimensional methods/problems. In this paper, the Lee’s method, is extended to three-dimensional discretization and is used to simulate high density ratio droplet penetration in randomly reconstructed porous media. Therefore, although the primary goal of this work is the extension of previous works [[23], [24], [25], [26]] to 3D; it is also extending the range of physical parameters investigated in available literature, i.e. mainly to higher density ratios as well as wider range of porosities.

The code is validated by Laplace’s law, relaxation of square droplet and also different equilibrium contact angles where simulation results are compared with Cahn’s wetting theory. The process of the droplet penetration in the porous substrate is then shown in detail. The effects of different parameters including, Froude number (Fr), Reynolds number (Re), Weber number (We), porosity (ε), contact angle (θ), and density ratio (ρl∕ρv) are investigated. Finally, the current 3D LBM methodology is extended for the multi-phase transport in a porous channel and the extraction of a droplet from a porous substrate to show the effectiveness of the utilized method for diverse pore-scale applications. To the authors best knowledge, the only available LBM results of the latter problem, i.e. droplet extraction from a porous medium, are in two-dimensional and presented by Taghilou and Rahimian [23]. Therefore, this manuscript also opens new horizon for treating such a problem using LBM.

2. Numerical model

Several LBM models have been developed to treat the multiphase problems. Some widely used models are for instances free-energy models [30], Shan–Chen model [16], and finite difference LBM [31]. One of the main drawbacks of these pioneered works is their limitations for high density ratio systems. New methods are proposed to overcome this shortcoming. For instance, a new free-energy model was developed by Inamuro et al. [32] which was able to achieve high-density ratios. However, because of solving the Pressure Poisson Equation the computational cost of this model is large. A simpler model, based on a Galilean-invariant free-energy, was developed by Zheng et al. [33] where, in contrast to the previous model, no pressure correction needs to be estimated. More recently, a new model based on He’s, Chen’s and Zhang’s (HCZ) interface tracking model [34] was developed by Lee [24] which is able to handle high-density ratio multiphase problems with a reasonable computational cost. In this model, intermolecular forces, expressed in form of potentials and the parasitic currents and initiates truncation errors of interfacial stresses, are eliminated. Later on, this model was extended for more complex problems with diverse applications [[18], [20], [35], [36], [37]]. In the next section, the 3D multiphase model of Lee [24] that we use in this work because of its ability for high density ratios is presented in more detail.

2.1. Governing equation

The mass balance equation for a system of two immiscible fluids with different densities and viscosities is (1)∂ρ̃i∂t+∇.qi=0.

We consider both fluids as incompressible. ρ̃i is the local density of the phase i (gas or liquid phase), t is time, and qi denotes the mass flow rate per unit volume of component i (qi=ρ̃iu and u is the volumetric flow averaged velocity). The total mass flow of component i is (2)qi=ρ̃iu−ρiji.

The total mass flow rate of each component is affected by the diffusive mass flow ρiji. Therefore, the volume diffusive flow rate for component i is (3)ρiji=ρ̃i(ui−u).

ρi and ui are the averaged density and volumetric flow velocity of the phase I, respectively. Thus, the local averaged density (ρ) is a function of local densities, (4)ρ=Cρl+(1−C)ρgwhere C=ρ̃l∕ρl is the liquid phase composition. Here, subscribes l and g denote the local properties of the liquid and gas phases, respectively. Therefore, the (1) can be re-written for either component as (5)∂C∂t+∇.uC−∇.jl=0,and (6)∂(1−C)∂t+∇.u(1−C)−∇.jg=0.

The volume diffusive flow rate is proportional to the chemical potential gradient (7)j=−M∇μ,with the mobility M>0. Combining Eqs. (5), (6), the mass balance equation is (8)∂C∂t+∇.uC=∇.(M∇μ).

For an immiscible system, according to Cahn and Hilliard [38], and assuming that the mixing energy of an isothermal system is related to its composition, Lee [24] suggested that the chemical potential μ can be written as (9)μ=μ0−k∇2Cwith μ0=∂E0∕∂C as the local gradient of the free energy E0. Knowing that jl=−jg at the interface, one can obtain the divergence of the velocity by summing Eqs. (5), (6) (10)∇.u=0.

Finally, in Lee’s model the interactions between the liquid–gas interface and solid wall appear in the surface integral of the total free energy as [24] (11)E=∫(E0C+k2|∇C|2)dV+∫ϕ0−ϕ1Cs+ϕ2Cs2−ϕ3Cs2+⋯dS,where E0=βC2(C−1)2 is the bulk energy and ϕi with i=0,1,2,… is a constant coefficient. Here, β is a constant, k is the gradient parameter, and Cs is the phase composition at a solid surface.

2.2. Three-dimensional discrete Boltzmann equations

For an incompressible binary fluid system, the discrete form of the Boltzmann equation (DBE) for mass and momentum distributions is originally proposed to model non-ideal van der Waals fluids (12)∂∂t+eα.∇fα=−1λfα−fαeq+1cs2eα−u.FΓαwhere eα is the αth-direction of the microscopic particle velocity, fα are the particle distribution functions, λ is the relaxation time, cs=c∕3 is the lattice speed of sound with c=δx∕δt being the lattice speed, and Γα=fαeq∕ρ. Here, fαeq is the equilibrium distribution function (13)fαeq=wαρ[1+eα.ucs2+eα.u22cs4−u.u2cs2],and δx and δt are the lattice spacing and time step, respectively. Finally, F represents intermolecular forces of a non-ideal gas, (14)F=∇ρcs2−∇p−C∇μC,where p is the dynamic pressure to enforce the incompressibility. In order to impose the body force effects, the source term (15)FB=gρl−ρgρl≠00ρl=0needs to be added on the right-hand side of the previous equation. Here, g is the gravitational acceleration.

A new distribution function (16)gα=fαcs2+p1−ρcs2Γα(0),transforms the evolution of pressure and momentum into their DBE forms. Therefore, the new equilibrium distribution function gαeq is (17)gαeq=fαeqcs2+p−ρcs2Γα(0)=wap+ρcs2eα.ucs2+(eα.u)22cs4−u.u2cs2.

It is noted that the 19-velocity model (known as D3Q19, see Fig. 1) is used in the present work in order to simulate three-dimensional problems. Therefore, the weighting coefficients, wα, in Eqs. (13), (17) are given by w0=1∕3, w1∼6=2∕36 and w7∼18=1∕36 for these 19 directions. The discrete velocity vector, eα, for either direction is (18)e0,e1,e2,e3,e4,e5,e6,e7,e8,e9,e10,e11,e12,e13,e14,e15,e16,e17,e18=010001000−1000−1000101−1011−100−1−101−1010110−1−1−10001−11101−10−1−10−11.

In order to account for the finite divergence of the velocity field within the interface, an additional distribution function hα=(C∕ρ)fα should be defined. This is important for problems where the divergence-free condition of the velocity is no longer satisfied, for instance, due to the gas/fluid volume generated by vaporization/condensation.

The modified DBEs for hα and gα, originally proposed for two-dimensional phase change application in [39], are adopted for our three-dimensional simulations (19)∂hα∂t+eα⋅∇hα=Cρ−1λfα−fαeq+eα−u⋅Fcs2Γα=−1λhα−hαeq+eα−u⋅∇C−Cρcs2∇p+C∇μΓα,and (20)∂gα∂t+eα⋅∇gα=−1λgα−gαeq+eα−u⋅∇ρcs2Γα−Γα0−C∇μΓα.

By applying the trapezoidal rule, the discrete forms of the modified composition and momentum distribution functions can be derived (21)h¯αx+eαδt,t+δt−h¯αx,t=−1τ+0.5h¯α−h¯αeqx,t+δteα−u∇C−Cρcs2∇p+C∇μΓαx,t+δt2M∇2μΓαx,t+δt2M∇2μΓαx+eαδt,t+δtand (22)g¯αx+eαδt,t+δt−g¯αx,t=−1τ+0.5g¯α−g¯αeqx,t+δteα−u∇ρcs2Γα−Γα0−C∇μΓαx,t.

Here, τ=λ∕δt is the non-dimensional relaxation time and is attained by evaluating the kinematic viscosity v=τcs2δt [24].

Finally, the macroscopic composition, momentum and pressure values can be computed by taking the zero and first order moments of the modified distribution functions

(23)C=∑αh¯α,(24)ρu=1cs2∑αeαg¯α−δt2C∇μ,and (25)p=∑αg¯α+δt2u⋅∇ρcs2,respectively.

It is noted that, the gradient and Laplacian terms for the hypothetical quantity ∅ are calculated using (26)∂∅∂Xi=∑α≠0wαeα.iˆ[∅(x+eαδt)−∅(x−eαδt)]2cs2δt,and (27)∂2∅∂Xi2=∑α≠0wα[∅(x+eαδt)−2∅(x)+∅(x−eαδt)]cs2δt2and are second-order accurate compact relations. It is noted that in Eq. (26), iˆ is the unit vector pointing along the ith-coordinate axis (i.e. x, y or z axis).

2.3. Boundary conditions

Applying two excessive boundary conditions is necessary for the simulation of solid surfaces in Lee’s model. First, no mass flux boundary condition resultsin zero chemical potential gradients in the direction normal to the solid boundary: (28)n.∇μ|s=0where n is the unit vector normal to the surface. By minimizing the total free energy against C, one can obtain the second type of boundary condition [24]: (29)n.∇C|s=−∅1k,where ∅1 is a constant parameter known as wetting potential. The first and second derivatives of C with respect to the direction perpendicular to the wall on the solid surfaces are evaluated as:

(30)∂C∂zz=0=−φk,and (31)∂2C∂z2z=0≈12−3∂C∂zz=0+4∂C∂zz=1−∂C∂zz=2,with (32)φ=∅12kβ,where it is assumed that z is the direction perpendicular to the wall and φ is the dimensionless wetting potential. The parameter β is an amplitude parameter to control the interaction energy between the two phases and k is a coefficient that is related to the surface tension and the thickness of the interface layer.

The last term on the right-hand side of Eq. (31) can be discretized as (33)∂C∂zz=2=12(3Cz=2−4Cz=1+Cz=0).

Unknown particle distribution functions at the wall sides are obtained from the bounce-back rule. Solid obstacles are randomly distributed to reproduce artificial porous media. The solid cells are distinguished from fluid cells by a void fraction parameter. This random parameter is equal to unity when a cell is located in the solid and is zero elsewhere. The total volume of solid cells must produce the desired porosity. For simplicity, the wall of each obstacle is considered as a flat plate and it has a minimum thickness of two lattices in each direction.

3. Result and discussion

3.1. Code verification and model validation

In order to verify the three-dimensional multiphase model as well as the numerical convergence, three different test cases namely, release of cubic droplet, Laplace’s law and Young’s law are investigated in the following.

3.1.1. Release of cubic droplet

This test case aims at showing the efficiency of the surface tension implemented in the code. Here, a cubic droplet with the initial length of 25 lu (lattice unit) is located in the middle of the computational domain with the size of Nx×Ny×Nz=60×60×60lu3, respectively, in x-, y- and z-directions. Fig. 2 shows the dynamic droplet deformation at its initial (T=0 ts), intermediate (T=900 ts) and final (T=3000 ts) time steps. As can be seen, after release of the droplet, it begins to reshape due to surface tension to minimize its energy. Finally, the droplet attains a perfect spherical shape and retains its shape for the rest of the simulation time. It is noted that the multiphase interface in Fig. 2 represents the iso-surfaces of liquid phase composition at contour level C = 0.5. The same interface representation is used in the rest of the manuscript unless it is stated otherwise.

3.1.2. Laplace’s law

The pressure difference across the interface of a static spherical droplet under the surface tension force is investigated for the second test case. The pressure difference across the droplet interface has a direct relation to surface tension (σ) and an inverse relation to the initial droplet radius (R0) and should follow Laplace’s law (34)ΔP=2σR0.

Fig. 3 presents pressure differences across the droplet interface under the influence of the surface tension force for several droplet radii and surface tension magnitudes. Overall 15 different σ and R0 combinations are performed for four different mesh resolutions. The results shown in Fig. 3 correspond to the mesh M2 as presented in Table 1. The numerical results are in good agreement with the analytical solution confirming the accuracy of the code for quiescent spherical droplets.

In order to show mesh independency in the Laplace’s law problem, the calculation is performed in periodic three-dimensional lattice systems of 403, 603, 803 and 1003 lu3 for the domain sizes corresponding to, here after called, M1, M2, M3 and M4 meshes, respectively. The quantitative comparison of the pressure differences, their relative errors when compared to Laplace’s law as well as their computational costs are shown in Table 1. The maximum error between the LBM prediction and the exact solution is 4% using mesh M1. This discrepancy reduced to 0.2% by increasing the mesh resolution to M4. On the other hand, the computational costs approximately increase linearly by increasing the mesh resolution. Therefore, a good trade-off between the accuracy and computational costs is mesh M2. As a consequence, we will use this mesh in the remainder of the manuscript. With this choice, the computational error is limited to less than 2%. Comparison between theoretical and calculated values indicated that the lattice Boltzmann model was in a good agreement with the Laplace’s law even for the coarse mesh case. It is noted that the initial radius is chosen to be only 10 lu and can magnify the accuracy of the utilize model even for coarse meshes engaged in the interfacial force calculation.

3.1.3. Young’s law

For the third test case, the contact angles between the liquid–gas and solid surface for wide range of non-wetting and wetting regions are simulated and compared to the analytical solution. This test case shows the accuracy of the two-phase LBM when the gas–liquid interface is in contact with the solid surface.

Briant et al. [[40], [41]] investigated the contact angle using the free energy LBM. They showed that, by minimizing the surface free energy, the contact angle can be related to the gradient of the surface order parameter. According to Young’s equation, the angle between the liquid–gas interface and the wall (θeq) can be expressed as (35)cosθeq=σsg−σslσlg.

The solid–gas (σsg) and solid–liquid (σsl) surface tensions can obtain as [[40], [41]]:

(36)σsg=−∅1Cs+σlg2−σlg2(1−φ)3∕2and (37)σsl=−∅1Cs+σlg2−σlg2(1+φ)3∕2.

The above equation is incorporated in the equilibrium distribution function and is used to impose the partial wetting condition near the wall.

By substituting Eqs. (36), (37) in Eq. (35), we get (38)cosθeq=(1+φ)1.5−(1−φ)1.52.

The inverse form of Eq. (38) in the range of 0 <θeq <π is (39)φ=2sgnπ2−θeq[cosarccossin2θeq3×1−cosarccossin2θeq3]1∕2.

In this test case, a liquid droplet with a radius of 20 lu is initially located tangential to the bottom surface of a computational domain with size of Nx×Ny×Nz=80×60×80lu3. Fig. 4 presents the final shape of the droplets for three different cases, namely with a very low θeq=140°, media θeq=90° and very high θeq=20° wettabilities. As can be seen the equilibrium contact angles are qualitatively in good agreement with the theoretical prediction.

The quantitative equilibrium contact angles along with the theoretical prediction curve as a function of dimensionless wetting potential for wide range of degree of wettability are presented in Fig. 5. There is a decent agreement between numerical and analytical results with a maximum relative error of less than 1% which shows the accuracy of our methodology while dealing with (non-)wetting surfaces.

3.2. Liquid droplets impinging on porous surfaces

In this section, the effect of different physical and flow parameters including, Reynolds, Froude, and Weber numbers as well as density ratio, contact angle and mean substance porosity on the droplet penetration in porous media is presented. The former dimensionless parameters are defined as (40)Re=−ρlu0R0μl,(41)Fr=u02gR0,(42)We=ρlu02R0σlg,for droplet penetration problem, where u0 and σlg are the initial droplet velocity and surface tension, respectively.

To show the complexity of multiphase fluid flow investigated in the current work, velocity streamlines and multiphase distribution flow field during the droplet penetration are shown in Fig. 6. Here, a liquid droplet with the initial diameter of 20 lu is impinged on the top of the porous substrate with the porosity of 0.65. A random numerical generation method is used to reconstruct the porous layer based on the porosity as representative property of the medium. It is noted that the computational domain has the size of Nx×Ny×Nz=50×50×100lu3. A bounce-back boundary condition is used for the interaction between the fluid particles and solid walls inside the porous domain. Free boundaries are fixed at the top and bottom planes and periodic boundaries are set at lateral sides. Other flow parameters are Re=20, We=25, Fr=0.5 and ρl∕ρv=10.

As can be seen in this figure, counter-rotating vortices are created due to the wake behind of the droplet at very initial stages of the impact. The direction of this rotation is counter clock wise (CCW) in the first quarter (see Fig. 6 a and e) following initial acceleration of the droplet. However, these counter-rotating vortices change the direction following the droplet deceleration step (see Fig. 6 e to h). The magnitude of these vortices decreases during the penetration process while droplet settling in. At this step droplet starts to penetrate inside the porous media mainly due to the capillary forces. As consequences, it creates very complex flow patterns (several recirculation zones, multi-direction stream lines, etc.) and interfacial shapes (several bubble entrapments, folding, breakups, etc.) inside the porous substrate.

It is noted that like most numerical methods, LBM also suffers from conservation of mass. Therefore, to clarify this point, the mass of the liquid phase in penetration problem of Fig. 6 is calculated in time and is presented in Fig. 7. As can be seen in this figure, although locally it changes by time, its average relative error value, |E|=|VNumerical−VExact|∕|VExact|, over time is limited to less that 1% (i.e. mass is conserved globally).

To examine the environment porosity effect, a liquid droplet with the same size is impinged on the top of three different porous media with a porosity of 0.15, 0.55 and 0.95. Fig. 8 illustrates the droplet penetration into these media at different computational times. The considered dimensionless numbers are Re=20, We=25, Fr=0.5, ρl∕ρv=10 and are kept constant for different cases. From this point forward, mainly the 3D view of the multiphase flow will be shown for simplicity.

The main mechanism for droplet penetration and spreading is the competition between the unbalanced capillary and the Young’s force [26]. For the wetting surface, we use θeq=60° throughout the remaining simulations in this article. The Young’s force tries to spread the droplet on the surface, as seen for a flat surface in Fig. 4 c and f. On the other hand, for such wettability angles, the fluid inside of the porous medium is concave and the capillary pressure is negative. Therefore, due to the difference of the pressure inside and outside of the pore, the flow will be injected into the porous substrate through the penetration mechanism.

It can be seen in Fig. 9 that as the porosity decreases the droplet penetration rate decreases. At the same time the spreading on the surface increases. Therefore, one may conclude that the Young’s force is dominated at very low porosities. On the other hand, by increasing the medium porosity, the droplet moves to large empty areas on its preferential transport pathway and, therefore, multiphase penetration increases.

The capillary pressure depends on the dimensions of the capillaries and the contact angle between the liquid and solid surfaces (43)pc=−4σlgcosθeqdpores.

Reis et al. [42] have extracted the following non-dimensional value of the capillary pressure for the substrate with spherical obstacles (44)pc=c3αcosθeqWeε3∕2(1−ε)Da1∕2,where c3=0.327 and α is a porous medium structure constant which is related to the pores’ diameter. Also Darcy number reads as (45)Da=KR02,with K being the permeability of the medium (not investigated in this work). This correlation describes the dependency of the capillary pressure on contact angle, porosity, Darcy number and Weber number. As can be seen in this equation, the porosity has direct effect on the capillary pressure and the stronger capillary pressure tends to produce larger gradients inside of the liquid droplet in the porous media. This effect compensates for the dissipation of momentum by drag forces and maintains higher fluid velocities inside of the substrate. Since there is less liquid outside of the substrate to spread laterally, this action reduces the lateral spreading. Therefore, the dynamic of the droplet in high porosity media are dominated by the unbalanced capillary force.

To investigate the penetration rate more quantitatively, we introduce two dimensionless parameters namely, non-absorbed (h∗=h∕D) and penetration (v∗=1−Vout∕Vtotal) coefficients where h, D, Vtotal and Voutare the height of the droplet outside of the porous medium, initial diameter of the droplet, droplet total volume and its portioned volume that is outside of the porous medium, respectively.

Fig. 9 presents the non-absorbed and penetration coefficients as a function of time for different media porosities corresponding to Fig. 8. It is seen that for the substrate with the porosity of ε=0.15, the penetration coefficient remains relatively constant, especially for the time less than 200, while the non-absorbed coefficient reduces rapidly. This signifies the spreading phenomena in this test case (see also Fig. 8 a to d). Although, increasing the porosity to ε=0.55 caused an initial rapid drop in penetration coefficient, its non-absorbed counterpart follows the same pattern as before, at least for the time less than 200. Therefore, one may expect a strong competition between the capillary and Young forces. This competition is also visible in Fig. 8 e and f where the droplet initially spreads on the surface and at the same time penetrating into the porous medium. Even at later time one may see an equally span-/stream-wise distributed droplet (see Fig. 8 g and h). However, for the substrate with the porosity of ε=0.95, a sudden drop in penetration coefficient suggests that the penetration is dominant in this case. Almost equally dropping the penetration and non-absorbed coefficients also indicates that the droplet keeps its shape for relatively long time as seen in Fig. 8 i and j. However, as the capillary force being dominant in the domain, the droplet eventually will be elongated in the stream-wise direction (see Fig. 8 k and l). It is noted that the droplets can penetrate in all presented media if they have sufficient time.

Fig. 10 presents the time snapshot of bubble penetrations into a porous medium with different density ratios and a porosity of ε=0.85. Three different density ratios namely ρl∕ρg=5,10 and 100 are investigated while keeping other dimensionless parameters constant at Re=20, We=20 and Fr=0.5. Therefore, according to Eqs. (40), (44), while the balance between the capillary and Young’s forces untouched, the liquid inertial forces are increased by an increment in the density ratio. As a consequence, the droplet has higher kinetic energy to penetrate into lower levels of the porous media. On contrary, by decreasing the density ratios, the inertia force is decreased and as a result the ability of a droplet to penetrate into the same substrate is decreased.

Fig. 11 shows the non-absorbed and penetration coefficients as a function of time for density ratios according to Fig. 10. Both coefficients increase with increasing density ratio. Therefore, we conclude that increasing the density ratio acts in the favour of the droplet penetration by providing higher inertial forces.

Fig. 12 presents the simulation results of droplet penetration in medium with a porosity of ε=0.85 at Froude numbers Fr=0.1,0.5 and 5. Other dimensionless parameters are kept constant at Re=20, We=20, ρl∕ρg=10. The Froude number is a dimensionless number that indicates the ratio of the flow inertia to the external field, here is the body force due to the gravity. Increasing the Froude number, or reduction of gravity, leads to a raise of the resistance against penetration. In Fig. 12 at Fr=5, the droplet is not significantly penetrating into the substrate. This is shown more quantitatively in Fig. 13 by plotting the non-absorbed and penetration coefficients for different Froude numbers. At this relatively high Froude number although the non-absorbed parameter decreases relatively fast, its penetration counterpart has a rather low slope. This indicates that spreading is the dominant mechanism at Fr=5.

As the Froude number decreases, the droplet overcomes the resistance of the substrate. Consequently, the penetration increases as seen in Fig. 12, Fig. 13. Finally, at Fr=0.1, the penetration becomes a dominant mechanism. It is noted that this finding is in contradiction with results reported by Reis et al. [42] in the sense that they found the droplet penetration is independent of this parameter. The reason is, in contrast to our work, the range of their Froude number (i.e. 100≤Fr≤5000) is in the high Froude limit where one can neglect the effects of external fields.

Fig. 14 shows the time evolution of the shape of the impinging of the droplet on the porous medium with the porosity of ε=0.85 for three different We numbers namely We=20,100 and We=400. The Weber number gives the relative importance of inertia in relation to surface tension. As the other parameters are maintained constant (i.e. Re=20, Fr=0.5 and ρl∕ρg=10), decreasing the value of Weber number represents an increase in the surface tension. As a result, the droplet tends to keep its shape for longer time. An increment in the surface tension also increases the capillary pressure. Therefore, one may expect higher penetration into a porous substrate at lower weber numbers. This can be clearly seen in Fig. 15 where both the non-absorbed and penetration coefficients, drop faster for lower Weber values. Fig. 15 is also indicating that, at these Weber numbers (except for the case of We=20) and maintaining other parameters constant, the surface tension has probably a little influence on the droplet penetration. Therefore, almost all of the curves in this Fig. 15 are close to each other.

Fig. 16 represents the time evolution of droplet shape during penetration into a substrate with a porosity of ε=0.85 for Re=5,20 and 40. Other dimensionless parameters are We=20,Fr=0.5, and ρl∕ρg=10. The Reynolds number is expressed as the ratio of inertial forces to viscous forces. By increasing the Reynolds number, the effect of viscosity decreases and consequently the total momentum dissipation of the droplet reduces. The less dissipation has two main consequences: (i) more axial momentum is directed to the lateral momentum and (ii) less drag dissipation on the droplet inside the substrates. While the former origins the larger initial spreading of the droplet on the surface and the latter causes its higher penetration into the substrate. In Fig. 16, at Re=5, the droplet is not spreading on the surface due to comparable inertia and dissipation forces and, as a result, less momentum redirection. It also penetrates slowly into the substrate due to a relatively high drag dissipation. However, for higher Reynolds numbers where the viscous effects are small compared to inertial effects, the droplet initially spreads wider on the surface and then penetrates into the porous medium.

These phenomena are also confirmed by Fig. 17 where the non-absorbed and penetration coefficients are presented as a function of time for different Reynolds numbers. Both parameters decrease more quickly when the Reynolds number is increased.

Finally, Fig. 18 presents the simulation results of droplet penetration in medium with a porosity of ε=0.85 for three different contact angles namely, θeq=30°,60° and 90°. As before, all other dimensionless parameters are kept the same at Fr=0.5,Re=20, We=20, and ρl∕ρg=10. As mentioned earlier, the contact angle characterizes the wettability of droplet and porous medium. The smaller values of contact angles suggest the more concavity for the fluid inside the porous medium. Therefore, droplet feels more negative capillary pressure inside of the substrate. As a consequence, it spreads more inside of the domain and more uniformly in all directions (see Fig. 18 a to d). This is shown more quantitatively in Fig. 19 by plotting the non-absorbed and penetration coefficients for different contact angles.

For the higher values of θeq the surface has lower wettability. Therefore, as expected, the spreading is decreased (see Fig. 18 i to l). Additionally, for the angles θeq≥90° the fluid inside of the porous media is not concave anymore. Therefore, there is no negative pressure to eject the droplet inside of the pores. Therefore, only long-term forces that may cause the droplet penetration are the gravitational accelerations and inertial forces. For θeq=120° (not shown here) the droplet stays mainly outside of the porous substrate till the end of the simulation (i.e. T=880 ts).

3.3. Multiphase flow transport in porous channel and bubble extraction problems

In this section, we show the applicability of the pore-scale multiphase LBM model in diverse applications such as multiphase flow in a porous channel and bubble extraction from a porous substrate. In the problem of fluid transport in a randomly reconstructed porous channel, the velocity inlet at given Reynolds number and the pressure outlet boundary conditions are imposed on the top and bottom planes, respectively. Additionally, periodic boundary conditions are used on lateral planes. As before, a bounce back boundary condition is used to assure no penetration into the solid part of the substrate.

Fig. 20 shows the transient multiphase transport process inside the porous media at different porosities ε=0.75 and ε=0.95 and different Reynolds numbers Re=10 and Re=20. At the early stage of the transport process, the liquid phase flows relatively uniform into the substrate regardless of the porosity and/or Reynolds number. This is mainly because of the uniform inflow profile at the top inlet. Inside of the channel, however, liquid water transport is mainly controlled by the competition between the capillary pressure and the inertial forces. As in the case of droplet impinging into a porous medium, the porosity has direct effect on the capillary pressure. Therefore, by increasing the porosity from ε=0.75 to ε=0.95, multiphase penetration inside of the porous media increases. Additionally, due to the less resistance, the liquid prefers to flow through larger pores. Hence, liquid in small pores tends to flow to larger, neighbouring pores.

On the other hand, keeping the porosity constant at ε=0.75, the flow penetration inside the porous media is increasing with higher Reynolds number. This is mainly due to the augmentation in the inertial forces. Additionally, regardless of the porosity and Reynolds number, the liquid phase stream breaks up in the porous media under certain conditions. As the pore becomes larger, the connecting resistance caused by surface tension will be weakened. As a result, the liquid phase detaches from its main stream. We qualitatively found that this phenomenon is increased by increasing the Reynolds number and increasing the porosity.

The last test case is a droplet extraction from a porous medium. The computational domain in this problem is the same as before (i.e. Nx×Ny×Nz=50×50×100lu3) where the upper half of it is filled with randomly constructed porous media. The droplet with the initial diameter of 25 lu is located at the centre of the porous region and flows downwards due to gravity. As in the droplet impinging problem, the lateral boundaries are chosen to be periodic and upper and lower parts of computational domain are set to be free boundaries.

Four snapshots of the bubble extraction process through two different porous media (i.e. ε=0.85 and ε=0.95) subjected to two different gravitational forces (namely g=0.05 and g=0.1) are presented in Fig. 21. Here the density ratio is ρl∕ρg=100 and simulation results are presented at the same computational time step, i.e. T=320 ts. As expected, by increasing the body force and/or porosity, the droplet will be extracted faster from the substrate. It is noted that the droplet extraction from a porous substrate is not well investigated in three-dimensional simulations and needs a separate extensive study.

It is also valuable to bring this fact into attention that unlike three-dimensional model presented in this work, two-dimensional LBM models cannot involve the wide range of medium porosity. This is because in 2D domain the flow field will be blocked at low porosities. However, in order to clarify the differences between two and three-dimensional simulations, the time evolutions of the extraction of a droplet from the porous substrate with the porosity of ε=0.95 are presented in Fig. 22. Here, g=0.1 and ρl∕ρg=100 are kept the same for the sake of comparison. As can be seen the two-dimensional simulations mimic their corresponding three-dimensional ones at least for lower physical times. However, while the time passes the differences are more pronounced. This is mainly because there are more degrees of freedom in 3D when compared to 2D simulations. Therefore, the initial droplet can move freely in other extra directions. Additionally, the contact angle may change along the contact line due to heterogeneities of the solid which causes different surface tensions which further signify the differences between two- and three-dimensional simulations. As can be seen in the final stage of the simulation, the extracted droplet from porous media is getting back its spherical shape which cannot be exactly reproduced in 2D (i.e. it mimics a long cylinder rather than a sphere). This further manifests the importance of the current three-dimensional simulations.

4. Conclusion

In this article, a three-dimensional lattice Boltzmann multiphase model is extended to simulate multiphase penetration into the porous media. The presented model was based on the multiphase model of Lee, which is capable of simulating problems with high-density ratios. The model is validated against the analytical solution of Young’s law, Laplace’s law and release of a square drop. Then, the penetration of multiphase flows and droplet penetration/extraction in/from the porous substrate are investigated. The porous media are generated randomly with square obstacles.

Flow characteristics such as the Reynolds number, the Weber number, the Froude number, porosity, contact angle and density ratio effects on the dynamics of droplet penetration have been investigated and their numerical results were shown both qualitatively and quantitatively. For the droplet impinging on the porous surface, it was found that increasing Froude number causes the droplet spreading over the surface. On the other hand, increasing Reynolds number, Weber number, density ratio and media porosity will enhance the droplet penetration into the porous substrate. Finally, by decreasing the contact angle, droplet spreads wider on the surface and penetrates more into the porous media. The reasons are explained by comparing the competence of active forces in the problem.

Additionally, the effect of porosity and Reynolds number on flow penetration in a reconstructed porous channel is investigated. It was found that both increasing the porosity and Reynolds number will enhance the flow penetration into the channel. Furthermore, it was found that the liquid detachment is increased by increasing these two parameters. Finally, some sample test cases are solved for a bubble extraction process from a porous medium. It was shown that the extraction process facilitates by an augmentation in body forces and/or substrate porosity. Additionally, a comparison between two- and three-dimensional results suggested that a former model is not able to completely mimic the later one for long physical times while dealing with complex flow behaviour with larger degree of freedoms. The detail investigation of extraction process and three-dimensional effects is left for our future work.
